# TypeScript style

The authoritative external references are the
[Google TypeScript Style Guide](https://google.github.io/styleguide/tsguide.html)
and the [TypeScript Handbook](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/intro.html).
Rules below either match or tighten them.

## Formatting

- **Formatter:** [Biome](https://biomejs.dev/) if the project uses it,
  Prettier otherwise. Never hand-format. Run via `npm run format` /
  the project's package script.
- **Line length:** 100. Trailing commas everywhere.
- **Semicolons:** yes. (Both Biome and Prettier defaults; the
  no-semicolon style breaks too many ASI edge cases.)

## TypeScript version and compiler

- **TypeScript 5.4+** minimum. Use a recent version (5.7+).
- `tsconfig.json` must enable **strict mode** at a minimum:

  ```jsonc
  {
    "compilerOptions": {
      "strict": true,                     // enables all strict checks
      "noUncheckedIndexedAccess": true,   // arr[i] is T | undefined
      "noImplicitOverride": true,
      "noFallthroughCasesInSwitch": true,
      "noUnusedLocals": true,
      "noUnusedParameters": true,
      "exactOptionalPropertyTypes": true,
      "moduleResolution": "Bundler",      // or "NodeNext"
      "verbatimModuleSyntax": true,
      "isolatedModules": true,
      "target": "ES2022",
      "module": "ESNext"
    }
  }
  ```

  Don't loosen these. If you must, justify it in a comment next to the
  override.

## `any` is banned

- `any` defeats the entire point of TypeScript. The lint catches it;
  don't suppress.
- For genuinely-unknown input (untrusted JSON, dynamic plugins, etc.),
  use `unknown` and **narrow** with type predicates or schema
  validation (`zod`, `valibot`, `arktype`).
- For library types you can't be bothered to model yet, `unknown`,
  not `any`. The cost of `unknown` (you must narrow) is the feature.

## Naming

- `camelCase` — variables, functions, methods, properties, file names
  for modules (`orderService.ts`, not `OrderService.ts`).
- `PascalCase` — types, interfaces, classes, enums, type parameters.
- `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE` — module-level constants that are truly
  compile-time constants. Not for `const x = foo()` (that's just a
  `const` binding).
- `_underscorePrefix` — never. TS has `private`/`#private`. Use them.
- Boolean names are predicates: `isReady`, `hasPayment`, `canRefund`.
- Don't abbreviate: `userCount`, not `uc`. Two-letter exceptions for
  well-known terms (`id`, `db`, `ui`) are fine.

## Type design

- Prefer `type` aliases over `interface` for new code. The differences
  are subtle (interfaces merge, types don't); types are stricter and
  compose more cleanly with conditional types.
- Use `interface` only when you genuinely want declaration merging
  (rare — typically for augmenting third-party types).
- Use `readonly` aggressively. `readonly T[]`, `readonly Map`, `as
  const` for literal-typed objects. Mutation is a deliberate choice,
  not a default.
- Use discriminated unions for sum types:

  ```ts
  type Result<T> =
    | { ok: true; value: T }
    | { ok: false; error: string };
  ```

  Adding a variant forces every `switch` to update. See `patterns.md`.

- Use **branded types** for domain primitives that need identity:

  ```ts
  type UserId = string & { readonly brand: unique symbol };
  function userId(s: string): UserId { return s as UserId; }
  ```

## Imports and modules

- ES modules only (`import` / `export`). Never `require`.
- Named exports by default. Default exports only for framework
  conventions (e.g. Next.js pages, certain webpack plugin formats).
- `import type` for types you only use in type positions. This drops
  the runtime import (and `verbatimModuleSyntax` will enforce it).
- Import order (Biome / ESLint can sort): node builtins → external
  packages → first-party (`@/...`) → relative (`./...`, `../...`).
- No barrel files (`index.ts` that re-exports everything) in
  application code. They wreck tree-shaking and create circular import
  hazards. Library packages may have a single root barrel as the
  public entry.

## Docs

- Use TSDoc (`/** ... */`) for exported items. Editor hover relies on
  it.

  ```ts
  /**
   * Calculates the area of a circle.
   *
   * @param radius - The radius of the circle. Must be non-negative.
   * @returns The area as `π * radius²`.
   * @throws {RangeError} If `radius` is negative.
   *
   * @example
   * ```ts
   * circleArea(1); // → 3.14159…
   * ```
   */
  export function circleArea(radius: number): number {
    if (radius < 0) throw new RangeError("radius must be non-negative");
    return Math.PI * radius * radius;
  }
  ```

## Error handling

- For application code, exceptions are fine (TS doesn't have checked
  exceptions). Throw a *specific* `Error` subclass; the catch site can
  `instanceof` it.
- For domain code that wants explicit errors, use the `Result<T, E>`
  pattern (see `patterns.md`) — keeps the type system honest about
  failure modes.
- Never throw a plain string. `throw new Error("…")` minimum;
  `throw new MyDomainError("…", { cause: original })` better.
- `catch` blocks: `catch (err: unknown)` — that's the default in
  strict mode. Narrow with `instanceof Error` or your own predicates.

## Async

- `async`/`await` only. No raw `.then()` chains in new code.
- `Promise.all` for parallelism; `Promise.allSettled` when failures
  shouldn't short-circuit the others.
- Don't forget `await` (the lint catches floating promises — keep it
  on).
- Don't mix sync and async in the same function signature. Pick one.
- Top-level `await` is fine in ESM entry points; don't use it in
  library code that may be imported by older bundlers.

## Loose ends to avoid

- `enum` — discriminated unions or `as const` objects are stricter,
  tree-shake better, and don't generate runtime code that surprises
  bundlers. Plain `enum` is acceptable for legacy interop; prefer
  alternatives in new code.
- `namespace` — use ES modules.
- `// @ts-ignore` and `// @ts-expect-error` without a comment.
  `@ts-expect-error` is preferred (it errors when no longer needed),
  and either form must explain *why*.
- `as` casts that aren't justified. `as unknown as T` is a code smell;
  fix the upstream type or write a real type predicate.
- `Function` as a type. Use a precise function type (`(x: number) =>
  string`) or `(...args: never[]) => unknown` if truly generic.
- `object` as a type. Use `Record<string, unknown>` or — better — a
  specific shape.
